You again? Hey, you! Don't move, or I'll...

207
00:18:41,369 --> 00:18:43,655
This was a short footage of stealth mechanics.

208
00:18:43,655 --> 00:18:47,345
It's interesting because most of these nuances

209
00:18:47,345 --> 00:18:49,130
won't be clearly noticed by players.

210
00:18:49,812 --> 00:18:53,454
If your game is played in playtest, they won't say,

211
00:18:53,454 --> 00:18:57,316
I like the fact that the low cello entered when I was getting close to the quad,

212
00:18:57,316 --> 00:18:59,958
but they will feel it strongly.

213
00:18:59,958 --> 00:19:04,401
And that's when you start adding layers of emotions on top of the game, thanks to audio.

214
00:19:04,401 --> 00:19:08,423
And we study on the engines such as Wwise or Fmod or Unity,

215
00:19:08,423 --> 00:19:11,365
we really have powerful tools for audio.

216
00:19:11,365 --> 00:19:13,966
It's really possible to work on the whole audioscape.

217
00:19:13,966 --> 00:19:17,168
And that's what interactivity really is.

218
00:19:17,348 --> 00:19:20,569
making the soundscape evolve following player selection.

219
00:19:20,569 --> 00:19:23,810
Let's get back to music and music grammar.

220
00:19:23,810 --> 00:19:28,371
Creating a musical grammar is essential, but what is also interesting

221
00:19:28,371 --> 00:19:31,712
is to use this grammar in different situations and contexts.

222
00:19:31,712 --> 00:19:35,393
It can help connecting gameplay and story for example,

223
00:19:35,393 --> 00:19:37,873
and that's the key for giving depth to a soundtrack.

